  "level": "A1",
  "summary": "Numbers 1-10 — you'll hear these constantly, for prices, time, and phone numbers.",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "id": "l1",
      "title": "Wahed to khamsa",
      "teach": [
        {
          "target": "wahed",
          "roman": "wahed",
          "arabic": "واحد",
          "english": "one",
          "ipa": "ˈwaħed"
        },
        {
          "target": "jouj",
          "roman": "jouj",
          "arabic": "جوج",
          "english": "two",
          "note": "Not from Arabic 'ithnan' at all — jouj is a Darija-specific word.",
          "ipa": "ʒuʒ"
        },
        {
          "target": "tlata",
          "roman": "tlata",
          "arabic": "تلاتة",
          "english": "three",
          "ipa": "tlaˈta"
        },
        {
          "target": "rb3a",
          "roman": "rb3a",
          "arabic": "ربعة",
          "english": "four",
          "ipa": "ˈrbʕa"
        },
        {
          "target": "khamsa",
          "roman": "khamsa",
          "arabic": "خمسة",
          "english": "five",
          "ipa": "ˈxamsa"
        }
      ],
      "grammar": {
        "title": "Reading the digit letters",
        "body": "You'll see the same handful of digits standing in for Arabic sounds across every unit: **3** = ع (a throat sound, like a tight swallow), **7** = ح (a breathy h, further back than English h), **9** = ق (a k made deep in the throat). They're not arbitrary — Moroccans picked digits that visually resemble the Arabic letter they replace."
      }
    },
    {
